## Code for Signal Plot ##
fig, pl1 = plt.subplots(5, 1, sharex=True, figsize=(30, 23))  # Creating subplots of 5 rows and 1 columns
fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0)  # Internal spaces Deletion

# loop for line plots
for s in range(5):
    pl1[s].margins(x=0)  # deleteing x margin
    pl1[s].grid(ls=':', axis='x', linewidth=3)  # grid
    
    if s <= 3: 
        plots = [sig.P1, sig.P2, sig.P3, sig.P4]
        pl1[s].plot(plots[s], color='k', lw = 2.5, alpha=0.7)  # plots Genration
        pl1[s].set_ylabel(f'P{s+1}', fontsize=20)  # labels on y axes
        pl1[s].set_yticks([0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1], fontsize=20)  # ticks on y axis

## Code for Gene annotation plot ##

# dictionary generating for (+,-) Key value
Dix = [{"label": ' ', "med": 0, "q1": 0, "q3": 0, "whislo": 0, "whishi": 0, "fliers": ()} for k in range(2)] 


for i in range(9): 
    t = ann.type[i]  
    
    if t == 'transcript': 
        st = ann.start[i]
        sp = ann.stop[i]
        sd = ann.strand[i]

    elif t == 'exon':   
        if sd == '-':  
            l = 0
        else:
            l = 1
        Dix[l]["q1"], Dix[l]["q3"] = ann.start[i], ann.stop[i]  
        Dix[l]["label"], Dix[l]["whislo"], Dix[l]["whishi"] = sd, st, sp   
       
        # ploting whishker plot with bxp function 
        pl1[4].bxp(Dix, vert=False, patch_artist=True, widths=0.18, boxprops=dict(facecolor='k', alpha=0.9 ))
        
pl1[4].set_ylabel('Annotation', fontsize=20), pl1[4].set_xlabel('Genomic Position', fontsize=20)#  labels on y 
pl1[4].set_xticks(np.linspace(0, 20000, 9), fontsize=20);  # labels on x

1.4: Discussion

Pros

To demonstrate different viewpoints of genomic annotation with RNA binding protein locations, three separate visualisation approaches are used. The box plot explains the location of the gene transcript, including exons and introns. Line plots, on the other hand, demonstrate RNA binding protein signals using different techniques, allowing for more in-depth analysis of research topics and adding credibility to the current data for future investigations.

Cons

The In-depth Heatmap display style is insufficient for properly expressing the present RNA signal data. Similarly, the overlapping lines in the group line charts make it difficult to differentiate the hidden lines behind each other, ultimately hiding the data.

## Bar plot ##

bar.columns = ['A', 'Condition1', 'Condition2', 'Control']   # column name assign
bar.A = bar.A.replace(['XY', 'XZ', 'YX', 'YZ'], ['XY', 'XZ', 'YX', 'YZ'])   # x axis lables


bf = np.arange(len(bar.A))     
bs = [i + 0.25 for i in bf]
bt = [i + 0.25 for i in bs]  

pl3_2.bar(bf, bar.Condition1, width=0.25, edgecolor='white', color='k', alpha=0.8)  # assigning variable to plot
pl3_2.bar(bs, bar.Condition2, width=0.25, edgecolor='white', color='k', alpha=0.8)
pl3_2.bar(bt, bar.Control, width=0.25, edgecolor='white', color='r', alpha=0.8)



pl3_2.set_xticks([r + 0.25 for r in range(len(bf))], ['XY', 'XZ', 'YX', 'YZ'], fontsize=20); # X axis labels
pl3_2.legend(('Condition1','Condition2','Control') ,fontsize=26)   # Legend for the plot
pl3_2.grid(True, axis='y', linestyle=':', linewidth=2, zorder = 0)  # grids 
pl3_2.set_ylabel('Number of events', fontsize=20)  # y label
pl3_2.set_xlabel('');

figure = fig.add_gridspec(nrows=2, ncols=1, hspace=0)

x = np.arange(0, value.shape[1], 1)
y = np.arange(0, value.shape[0], 1)

3: 2-mer Counts In Sequence Data

In [6]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15, 6))

# Reading the DNA sequences from the file
sequences = []
with open("/drive/notebooks/Data Visualisation 2/10_project_data_dna_sequences.txt", "r") as file:
    sequences = file.read().splitlines()

# Definning the k-mers to search letter
kmrs = ["AA", "AC", "AG", "AT", "CA", "CC", "CG", "CT", "GA", "GC", "GG", "GT", "TA", "TC", "TG", "TT"]

# creating list in list to store k-mer counts per position
counts = [[0] * len(sequences[0]) for t in range(len(kmrs))]

# Count the occurrences of k-mers at each position for all sequences
for sequence in sequences:
    for i in range(len(sequence) - 1):
        kmr = sequence[i:i+2]
        for j, k in enumerate(kmrs):
            if kmr == k:
                counts[j][i] += 1
                

data = [[i for i in j if i > 10] for j in counts] # Removing smaller values like 0 which is deeping the graph at the end
data[0].pop(198)

colormap = plt.cm.get_cmap('Spectral')  # Colormap set
for i, kmr in enumerate(kmrs): 
        normalized_value = i / (len(kmrs) - 1) # Calculate a value based on the index    
        line_color = colormap(normalized_value) # colors from the colormap based on the value
        plt.plot(range(len(data[i])), data[i], label=kmr, color=line_color, lw = 4)
    
# Decoration part of the plot
plt.xlabel("Position", fontsize = 14)
plt.ylabel("K-mer counts", fontsize = 14)
plt.xticks(fontsize = 14)
plt.yticks(fontsize = 14)
plt.legend(loc='upper right', bbox_to_anchor=(0.08, 0.99), fontsize=12)
plt.rcParams["figure.autolayout"] = True
plt.rcParams["axes.edgecolor"] = "black"
plt.rcParams["axes.linewidth"] = 1
plt.grid(ls='solid')
